# Keyboard shortcuts

The command line is a **tiny text editor**. Stop arrow-keying — move by **line and word**.

## Move & delete

- **Ctrl-A / Ctrl-E** — start / end of line
- **Ctrl-U / Ctrl-K** — delete to start / to end
- **Ctrl-W** — delete word before cursor
- **Ctrl-Y** — paste back what you deleted
- **Alt-B / Alt-F** — back / forward one word

## Control

- **Ctrl-L** — clear screen · **Ctrl-C** — abandon line
- **Ctrl-D** — end-of-input (empty prompt = log out)

## The magic one

**Alt-.** pastes the **last argument** of the previous command.
`mkdir /tmp/a/b/c` → `cd ` **Alt-.** → `cd /tmp/a/b/c`.

**Emacs-style** (bash default). Five minutes now saves hours.
